# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: organic-chemistry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] In organic chemistry, **aromaticity** is a chemical property describing the way in which a conjugated ring of unsaturated bonds, lone pairs, or empty orbitals exhibits a stabilization stronger than would be expected from conjugation alone.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] The earliest use of the term was in an article by August Wilhelm Hofmann in 1855.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] There is no general relationship between aromaticity as a chemical property and the olfactory properties of such compounds.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Aromaticity can also be considered a manifestation of cyclic delocalization and of resonance.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] This is usually considered to be because electrons are free to cycle around circular arrangements of atoms that are alternately single- and double-bonded to one another.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] This commonly seen model of aromatic rings, namely the idea that benzene was formed from a six-membered carbon ring with alternating single and double bonds (cyclohexatriene), was developed by Kekulé (see History section below).
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Each bond may be seen as a hybrid of a single bond and a double bond, every bond in the ring identical to every other.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] The model for benzene consists of two resonance forms, which corresponds to the double and single bonds superimposing to give rise to six one-and-a-half bonds.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Benzene is a more stable molecule than would be expected without accounting for charge delocalization.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] As is standard for resonance diagrams, a double-headed arrow is used to indicate that the two structures are not distinct entities, but merely hypothetical possibilities.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Neither is an accurate representation of the *actual* compound, which is best represented by a hybrid (average) of these structures, which can be seen at right.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] A C=C bond is shorter than a C−C bond, but benzene is perfectly hexagonal—all six carbon-carbon bonds have the same length, intermediate between that of a single and that of a double bond.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] A better representation is that of the circular π bond (Armstrong's *inner cycle*), in which the electron density is evenly distributed through a π-bond above and below the ring.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] This model more correctly represents the location of electron density within the aromatic ring.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] The single bonds are formed with electrons in line between the carbon nuclei — these are called σ-bonds.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Double bonds consist of a σ-bond and a π-bond.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] The π-bonds are formed from overlap of atomic p-orbitals above and below the plane of the ring.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Because they are out of the plane of the atoms, these orbitals can interact with each other freely, and become delocalized.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] This means that, instead of being tied to one atom of carbon, each electron is shared by all six in the ring.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Thus, there are not enough electrons to form double bonds on all the carbon atoms, but the "extra" electrons strengthen all of the bonds on the ring equally.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] The resulting molecular orbital has π symmetry.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] The first known use of the word "aromatic" as a *chemical* term — namely, to apply to compounds that contain the phenyl radical — occurs in an article by August Wilhelm Hofmann in 1855.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] If this is indeed the earliest introduction of the term, it is curious that Hofmann says nothing about why he introduced an adjective indicating olfactory character to apply to a group of chemical substances of which only some have notable aromas.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Also, many of the most odoriferous organic substances known are terpenes, which are not aromatic in the chemical sense.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] But terpenes and benzenoid substances do have a chemical characteristic in common, namely higher unsaturation indices than many aliphatic compounds, and Hofmann may not have been making a distinction between the two categories.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] In the 19th century, chemists found it puzzling that benzene could be so unreactive toward addition reactions, given its presumed high degree of unsaturation.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] The cyclohexatriene structure for benzene was first proposed by August Kekulé in 1865.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Over the next few decades, most chemists readily accepted this structure, since it accounted for most of the known isomeric relationships of aromatic chemistry.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Thomson, the discoverer of the electron, proposed three equivalent electrons between each carbon atom in benzene.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] An explanation for the exceptional stability of benzene is conventionally attributed to Sir Robert Robinson, who was apparently the first (in 1925) to coin the term *aromatic sextet* as a group of six electrons that resists disruption.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Here, Armstrong is describing at least four modern concepts.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] First, his "affinity" is better known nowadays as the electron, which was to be discovered only seven years later by J.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Second, he is describing electrophilic aromatic substitution, proceeding (third) through a Wheland intermediate, in which (fourth) the conjugation of the ring is broken.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] He introduced the symbol **C** centered on the ring as a shorthand for the *inner cycle*, thus anticipating Erich Clar's notation.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] The quantum mechanical origins of this stability, or aromaticity, were first modelled by Hückel in 1931.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] He was the first to separate the bonding electrons into sigma and pi electrons.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Coplanar structure, with all the contributing atoms in the same plane.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Contributing atoms arranged in one or more rings.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] A number of π delocalized electrons that is even, but not a multiple of 4 (that is, 4n + 2 for some integer n).
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] While benzene is aromatic, having 6 electrons from 3 double bonds, cyclobutadiene is not, since the number of π delocalized electrons is 4, which does not satisfy Hückel's rule.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] The cyclobutadienide(2−) ion, however, is aromatic, with 6 electrons.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] An atom in an aromatic system can have other electrons that are not part of the system, and which therefore do not affect Hückel's rule.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] In furan, for example, the oxygen atom is sp2 hybridized.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] One lone pair is in the π system and the other in the plane of the ring (analogous to the C-H bond in the other positions).
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] There are 6 π electrons, so furan is aromatic.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Aromatic molecules typically display enhanced chemical stability, compared to similar non-aromatic molecules.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] A molecule that can be aromatic will tend to alter its electronic or conformational structure to be in this situation.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] This extra stability changes the chemistry of the molecule.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Aromatic compounds undergo electrophilic aromatic substitution and nucleophilic aromatic substitution reactions, but not electrophilic addition reactions as happens with carbon-carbon double bonds.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Many of the earliest-known examples of aromatic compounds, such as benzene and toluene, have distinctive pleasant smells.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] This property led to the term "aromatic" for this class of compounds, and hence the term "aromaticity" for the eventually discovered electronic property.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] The circulating π electrons in an aromatic molecule produce ring currents that oppose the applied magnetic field in NMR.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] The NMR signal of protons in the plane of an aromatic ring are shifted substantially further down-field than those on non-aromatic sp2 carbons.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] This is an important way of detecting aromaticity.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] By the same mechanism, the signals of protons located near the ring axis are shifted up-field.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Aromatic molecules are able to interact with each other in so-called π-π stacking: The π systems form two parallel rings overlap in a "face-to-face" orientation.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Aromatic molecules are also able to interact with each other in an "edge-to-face" orientation: The slight positive charge of the substituents on the ring atoms of one molecule are attracted to the slight negative charge of the aromatic system on another molecule.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Planar monocyclic molecules containing 4n π electrons are called antiaromatic and are, in general, destabilized.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Molecules that could be antiaromatic will tend to alter their electronic or conformational structure to avoid this situation, thereby becoming non-aromatic.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] For example, cyclooctatetraene (COT) distorts itself out of planarity, breaking π overlap between adjacent double bonds.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Relatively recently, cyclobutadiene was discovered to adopt an asymmetric, rectangular configuration in which single and double bonds indeed alternate; there is no resonance and the single bonds are markedly longer than the double bonds, reducing unfavorable p-orbital overlap.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] This reduction of symmetry lifts the degeneracy of the two formerly non-bonding molecular orbitals, which by Hund's rule forces the two unpaired electrons into a new, weakly bonding orbital (and also creates a weakly antibonding orbital).
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Hence, cyclobutadiene is non-aromatic; the strain of the asymmetric configuration outweighs the anti-aromatic destabilization that would afflict the symmetric, square configuration.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Aromatic compounds play key roles in the biochemistry of all living things.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] The four aromatic amino acids histidine, phenylalanine, tryptophan, and tyrosine each serve as one of the 20 basic building-blocks of proteins.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Further, all 5 nucleotide bases (adenine, thymine, cytosine, guanine, and uracil) that make up the sequence of the genetic code in DNA and RNA are aromatic purines or pyrimidines.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] The molecule heme contains an aromatic system with 22 π electrons.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Chlorophyll also has a similar aromatic system.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Aromatic compounds are important in industry.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Key aromatic hydrocarbons of commercial interest are benzene, toluene, *ortho*-xylene and *para*-xylene.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] About 35 million tonnes are produced worldwide every year.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] They are extracted from complex mixtures obtained by the refining of oil or by distillation of coal tar, and are used to produce a range of important chemicals and polymers, including styrene, phenol, aniline, polyester and nylon.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] The overwhelming majority of aromatic compounds are compounds of carbon, but they need not be hydrocarbons.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Benzene, as well as most other [*n*]annulenes C*n*H*n* when *n* is twice an odd number, such as [14]annulene and [18]annulene. [10]annulenes are an exception as they are nonplanar to relieve high levels of ring strain.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] In heterocyclic aromatics (**heteroaromats**), one or more of the atoms in the aromatic ring is of an element other than carbon.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] This can lessen the ring's aromaticity, and thus (as in the case of furan) increase its reactivity.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Other examples include pyridine, pyrazine, imidazole, pyrazole, oxazole, thiazole, thiophene, and their benzannulated analogs (benzimidazole, for example).
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons are molecules containing two or more simple aromatic rings fused together by sharing two neighboring carbon atoms (see also simple aromatic rings).
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Examples are naphthalene, anthracene, and phenanthrene.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Many chemical compounds are aromatic rings with other functional groups attached.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Examples include trinitrotoluene (TNT), acetylsalicylic acid (aspirin), paracetamol, and the nucleotides of DNA.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Aromaticity is found in ions as well: the cyclopropenyl cation (2e system), the cyclopentadienyl anion (6e system), the tropylium ion (6e), and the cyclooctatetraene dianion (10e).
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Aromatic properties have been attributed to non-benzenoid compounds such as tropone.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Aromatic properties are tested to the limit in a class of compounds called cyclophanes.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] A special case of aromaticity is found in homoaromaticity where conjugation is interrupted by a single sp3 hybridized carbon atom.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] When carbon in benzene is replaced by other elements in borabenzene, silabenzene, germanabenzene, stannabenzene, phosphorine or pyrylium salts the aromaticity is still retained.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Aromaticity also occurs in compounds that are not carbon-based at all.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Inorganic 6-membered-ring compounds analogous to benzene have been synthesized.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Hexasilabenzene (Si6H6) and borazine (B3N3H6) are structurally analogous to benzene, with the carbon atoms replaced by another element or elements.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] In borazine, the boron and nitrogen atoms alternate around the ring.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Quite recently, the aromaticity of planar Si56- rings occurring in the Zintl phase Li12Si7 was experimentally evidenced by Li solid state NMR.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Metal aromaticity is believed to exist in certain metal clusters of aluminium.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Möbius aromaticity occurs when a cyclic system of molecular orbitals, formed from pπ atomic orbitals and populated in a closed shell by 4n (n is an integer) electrons, is given a single half-twist to correspond to a Möbius strip.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] A π system with 4n electrons in a flat (non-twisted) ring would be anti-aromatic, and therefore highly unstable, due to the symmetry of the combinations of p atomic orbitals.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] By twisting the ring, the symmetry of the system changes and becomes allowed (see also Möbius–Hückel concept for details).
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Because the twist can be left-handed or right-handed, the resulting Möbius aromatics are *dissymmetric* or chiral.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] As of 2012, there is no proof that a Möbius aromatic molecule was synthesized.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Aromatics with two half-twists corresponding to the paradromic topologies were first suggested by Johann Listing.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] In carbo-benzene the ring bonds are extended with alkyne and allene groups.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Y-aromaticity is a concept which was developed to explain the extraordinary stability and high basicity of the guanidinium cation.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] Guanidinium does not have a ring structure but has six π-electrons which are delocalized over the molecule.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] However, this concept is controversial and some authors have stressed different effects.
[src:organic-chemistry/aromaticity] The distinction of global vs local aromaticity also affects the detection of aromaticity in cheminformatics toolkits.
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] In organic chemistry, a **functional group** is any substituent or moiety in a molecule that causes the molecule's characteristic chemical reactions.
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] The same functional group will undergo the same or similar chemical reactions regardless of the rest of the molecule's composition.
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] This enables systematic prediction of chemical reactions and behavior of chemical compounds and the design of chemical synthesis.
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] The reactivity of a functional group can be modified by other functional groups nearby.
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] Functional group interconversion can be used in retrosynthetic analysis to plan organic synthesis.
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] A functional group is a group of atoms in a molecule with distinctive chemical properties, regardless of the other atoms in the molecule.
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] The atoms in a functional group are linked to each other and to the rest of the molecule by covalent bonds.
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] For repeating units of polymers, functional groups attach to their nonpolar core of carbon atoms and thus add chemical character to carbon chains.
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] Functional groups can also be charged, e.g. in carboxylate salts (−COO−), which turns the molecule into a polyatomic ion or a complex ion.
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] Functional groups binding to a central atom in a coordination complex are called *ligands*.
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] Complexation and solvation are also caused by specific interactions of functional groups.
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] In the common rule of thumb "like dissolves like", it is the shared or mutually well-interacting functional groups which give rise to solubility.
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] For example, sugar dissolves in water because both share the hydroxyl functional group (−OH) and hydroxyls interact strongly with each other.
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] Plus, when functional groups are more electronegative than atoms they attach to, the functional groups will become polar, and the otherwise nonpolar molecules containing these functional groups become polar and so become soluble in some aqueous environment.
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] Combining the names of functional groups with the names of the parent alkanes generates what is termed a systematic nomenclature for naming organic compounds.
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] In traditional nomenclature, the first carbon atom after the carbon that attaches to the functional group is called the alpha carbon; the second, beta carbon, the third, gamma carbon, etc.
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] If there is another functional group at a carbon, it may be named with the Greek letter, e.g., the gamma-amine in gamma-aminobutyric acid is on the third carbon of the carbon chain attached to the carboxylic acid group.
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] IUPAC conventions call for numeric labeling of the position, e.g.
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] In traditional names various qualifiers are used to label isomers, for example, isopropanol (IUPAC name: propan-2-ol) is an isomer of n-propanol (propan-1-ol).
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] The term moiety has some overlap with the term "functional group".
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] However, a moiety is an entire "half" of a molecule, which can be not only a single functional group, but also a larger unit consisting of multiple functional groups.
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] For example, an "aryl moiety" may be any group containing an aromatic ring, regardless of how many functional groups the said aryl has.
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] The following is a list of common functional groups.
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] In the formulas, the symbols R and R' usually denote an attached hydrogen, or a hydrocarbon side chain of any length, but may sometimes refer to any group of atoms.
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] Hydrocarbons are a class of molecule that is defined by functional groups called hydrocarbyls that contain only carbon and hydrogen, but vary in the number and order of double bonds.
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] Each one differs in type (and scope) of reactivity.
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] There are also a large number of branched or ring alkanes that have specific names, e.g., tert-butyl, bornyl, cyclohexyl, etc.
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] There are several functional groups that contain an alkene such as vinyl group, allyl group, or acrylic group.
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] Hydrocarbons may form charged structures: positively charged carbocations or negative carbanions.
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] Examples are tropylium and triphenylmethyl cations and the cyclopentadienyl anion.
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] Haloalkanes are a class of molecule that is defined by a carbon–halogen bond.
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] This bond can be relatively weak (in the case of an iodoalkane) or quite stable (as in the case of a fluoroalkane).
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] In general, with the exception of fluorinated compounds, haloalkanes readily undergo nucleophilic substitution reactions or elimination reactions.
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] The substitution on the carbon, the acidity of an adjacent proton, the solvent conditions, etc. all can influence the outcome of the reactivity.
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] Compounds that contain C–O bonds each possess differing reactivity based upon the location and hybridization of the C–O bond, owing to the electron-withdrawing effect of sp²-hybridized oxygen (carbonyl groups) and the donating effects of sp³-hybridized oxygen (alcohol groups).
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] Compounds that contain nitrogen in this category may contain C-O bonds, such as in the case of amides.
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] Compounds that contain sulfur exhibit unique chemistry due to sulfur's ability to form more bonds than oxygen, its lighter analogue on the periodic table.
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] Substitutive nomenclature (marked as prefix in table) is preferred over functional class nomenclature (marked as suffix in table) for sulfides, disulfides, sulfoxides and sulfones.
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] Compounds that contain phosphorus exhibit unique chemistry due to the ability of phosphorus to form more bonds than nitrogen, its lighter analogue on the periodic table.
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] Compounds containing boron exhibit unique chemistry due to their having partially filled octets and therefore acting as Lewis acids.
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] These names are used to refer to the moieties themselves or to radical species, and also to form the names of halides and substituents in larger molecules.
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] When the parent hydrocarbon is unsaturated, the suffix ("-yl", "-ylidene", or "-ylidyne") replaces "-ane" (e.g.
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] "ethane" becomes "ethyl"); otherwise, the suffix replaces only the final "-e" (e.g.
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] When used to refer to moieties, multiple single bonds differ from a single multiple bond.
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] For example, a methylene bridge (methanediyl) has two single bonds, whereas a methylidene group (methylidene) has one double bond.
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] Suffixes can be combined, as in methylidyne (triple bond) vs. methylylidene (single bond and double bond) vs. methanetriyl (three double bonds).
[src:organic-chemistry/functional-group] There are some retained names, such as methylene for methanediyl, 1,x-phenylene for phenyl-1,x-diyl (where x is 2, 3, or 4), carbyne for methylidyne, and trityl for triphenylmethyl.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] In chemistry, a **nucleophilic substitution** (**SN**) is a class of chemical reactions in which an electron-rich chemical species (known as a nucleophile) replaces a functional group within another electron-deficient molecule (known as the electrophile).
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] The molecule that contains the electrophile and the leaving functional group is called the substrate.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] The electron pair (**:**) from the nucleophile (Nuc) attacks the substrate (R−LG) and bonds with it.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] Simultaneously, the leaving group (LG) departs with an electron pair.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] The principal product in this case is R−Nuc.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] The nucleophile may be electrically neutral or negatively charged, whereas the substrate is typically neutral or positively charged.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] An example of nucleophilic substitution is the hydrolysis of an alkyl bromide, R-Br under basic conditions, where the attacking nucleophile is hydroxyl (OH−) and the leaving group is bromide (Br−).
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] Nucleophilic substitution reactions are common in organic chemistry.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] Nucleophiles often attack a saturated aliphatic carbon.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] Less often, they may attack an aromatic or unsaturated carbon.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] Hughes and Sir Christopher Ingold studied nucleophilic substitution reactions of alkyl halides and related compounds.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] They proposed that there were two main mechanisms at work, both of them competing with each other.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] The two main mechanisms were the SN1 reaction and the SN2 reaction, where *S* stands for substitution, *N* stands for nucleophilic, and the number represents the kinetic order of the reaction.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] In the SN2 reaction, the addition of the nucleophile and the elimination of leaving group take place simultaneously (i.e. a concerted reaction).
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] SN2 occurs when the central carbon atom is easily accessible to the nucleophile.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] In SN2 reactions, there are a few conditions that affect the rate of the reaction.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] First of all, the 2 in SN2 implies that there are two concentrations of substances that affect the rate of reaction: substrate (Sub) and nucleophile.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] The rate equation for this reaction would be Rate=k[Sub][Nuc].
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] For a SN2 reaction, an aprotic solvent is best, such as acetone, DMF, or DMSO.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] Aprotic solvents do not add protons (H+ ions) into solution; if protons were present in SN2 reactions, they would react with the nucleophile and severely limit the reaction rate.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] Since this reaction occurs in one step, steric effects drive the reaction speed.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] In the intermediate step, the nucleophile is 185 degrees from the leaving group and the stereochemistry is inverted as the nucleophile bonds to make the product.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] Also, because the intermediate is partially bonded to the nucleophile and leaving group, there is no time for the substrate to rearrange itself: the nucleophile will bond to the same carbon that the leaving group was attached to.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] A final factor that affects reaction rate is nucleophilicity; the nucleophile must attack an atom other than a hydrogen.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] By contrast the SN1 reaction involves two steps.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] SN1 reactions tend to be important when the central carbon atom of the substrate is surrounded by bulky groups, both because such groups interfere sterically with the SN2 reaction (discussed above) and because a highly substituted carbon forms a stable carbocation.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] Like SN2 reactions, there are quite a few factors that affect the reaction rate of SN1 reactions.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] Instead of having two concentrations that affect the reaction rate, there is only one, substrate.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] The rate equation for this would be Rate=k[Sub].
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] Since the rate of a reaction is only determined by its slowest step, the rate at which the leaving group "leaves" determines the speed of the reaction.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] This means that the better the leaving group, the faster the reaction rate.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] A general rule for what makes a good leaving group is the weaker the conjugate base, the better the leaving group.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] In this case, halogens are going to be the best leaving groups, while compounds such as amines, hydrogen, and alkanes are going to be quite poor leaving groups.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] As SN2 reactions were affected by sterics, SN1 reactions are determined by bulky groups attached to the carbocation.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] Since there is an intermediate that actually contains a positive charge, bulky groups attached are going to help stabilize the charge on the carbocation through resonance and distribution of charge.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] In this case, tertiary carbocation will react faster than a secondary which will react much faster than a primary.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] It is also due to this carbocation intermediate that the product does not have to have inversion.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] The nucleophile can attack from the top or the bottom and therefore create a racemic product.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] It is important to use a protic solvent, water and alcohols, since an aprotic solvent could attack the intermediate and cause unwanted product.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] It does not matter if the hydrogens from the protic solvent react with the nucleophile since the nucleophile is not involved in the rate determining step.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] An example of a substitution reaction taking place by a so-called **borderline mechanism** as originally studied by Hughes and Ingold is the reaction of *1-phenylethyl chloride* with sodium methoxide in methanol.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] The reaction rate is found to the sum of SN1 and SN2 components with 61% (3,5 M, 70 °C) taking place by the latter.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] Besides SN1 and SN2, other mechanisms are known, although they are less common.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] The **SNi** mechanism is observed in reactions of thionyl chloride with alcohols, and it is similar to SN1 except that the nucleophile is delivered from the same side as the leaving group.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] Nucleophilic substitutions can be accompanied by an allylic rearrangement as seen in reactions such as the Ferrier rearrangement.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] This type of mechanism is called an SN1' or SN2' reaction (depending on the kinetics).
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] With allylic halides or sulphonates, for example, the nucleophile may attack at the γ unsaturated carbon in place of the carbon bearing the leaving group.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] Nucleophilic substitution via the SN1 or SN2 mechanism does not generally occur with vinyl or aryl halides or related compounds.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] Under certain conditions nucleophilic substitutions may occur, via mechanisms described in the nucleophilic aromatic substitution article.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] Substitution at a carbonyl group, such as acyl chlorides and esters, generally proceeds via addition-elimination.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] In rare cases, nucleophilic substitution may proceed on a radical intermediate.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] The SN1cB mechanism appears in inorganic chemistry.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] In organometallic chemistry the nucleophilic abstraction reaction occurs with a nucleophilic substitution mechanism.
[src:organic-chemistry/nucleophilic-substitution] There are many reactions in organic chemistry involving nucleophilic substitution.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] For molecules showing color, the carbon atoms are in black, hydrogens in gray, and oxygens in red.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] In the line angle representation, carbon atoms are implied at every terminus of a line and vertex of multiple lines, and hydrogen atoms are implied to fill the remaining needed valences (up to 4).
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] The range of chemicals studied in organic chemistry includes hydrocarbons (compounds containing only carbon and hydrogen) as well as compounds based on carbon, but also containing other elements, especially oxygen, nitrogen, sulfur, phosphorus (included in many biochemicals) and the halogens.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Organometallic chemistry is the study of compounds containing carbon–metal bonds.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Organic compounds form the basis of all known life and constitute the majority of known chemicals.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] The bonding patterns of carbon, with its valence of four—formal single, double, and triple bonds, plus structures with delocalized electrons—make the array of organic compounds structurally diverse, and their range of applications enormous.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] They form the basis of, or are constituents of, many commercial products including pharmaceuticals; petrochemicals and agrichemicals, and products made from them including lubricants, solvents; plastics; fuels and explosives.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] The study of organic chemistry overlaps organometallic chemistry and biochemistry, but also with medicinal chemistry, polymer chemistry, and materials science.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Organic chemistry is typically taught at the college or university level.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] It is considered a very challenging course but has also been made accessible to students.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Before the 18th century, chemists generally believed that compounds obtained from living organisms were endowed with a vital force that distinguished them from inorganic compounds.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] According to the concept of vitalism (vital force theory), organic matter was endowed with a "vital force".
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] During the first half of the nineteenth century, some of the first systematic studies of organic compounds were reported.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Around 1816 Michel Chevreul started a study of soaps made from various fats and alkalis.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] He separated the acids that, in combination with the alkali, produced the soap.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Since these were all individual compounds, he demonstrated that it was possible to make a chemical change in various fats (which traditionally come from organic sources), producing new compounds, without "vital force".
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] In 1828 Friedrich Wöhler produced the *organic* chemical urea (carbamide), a constituent of urine, from *inorganic* starting materials (the salts potassium cyanate and ammonium sulfate), in what is now called the Wöhler synthesis.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Although Wöhler himself was cautious about claiming he had disproved vitalism, this was the first time a substance thought to be organic was synthesized in the laboratory without biological (organic) starting materials.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] The event is now generally accepted as indeed disproving the doctrine of vitalism.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] After Wöhler, Justus von Liebig worked on the organization of organic chemistry, being considered one of its principal founders.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] In 1856, William Henry Perkin, while trying to manufacture quinine, accidentally produced the organic dye now known as Perkin's mauve.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] His discovery, made widely known through its financial success, greatly increased interest in organic chemistry.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] A crucial breakthrough for organic chemistry was the concept of chemical structure, developed independently in 1858 by both Friedrich August Kekulé and Archibald Scott Couper.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Both researchers suggested that tetravalent carbon atoms could link to each other to form a carbon lattice, and that the detailed patterns of atomic bonding could be discerned by skillful interpretations of appropriate chemical reactions.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] The era of the pharmaceutical industry began in the last decade of the 19th century when the German company, Bayer, first manufactured acetylsalicylic acid—more commonly known as aspirin.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] By 1910 Paul Ehrlich and his laboratory group began developing arsenic-based arsphenamine (Salvarsan) as the first effective medicinal treatment of syphilis, and thereby initiated the medical practice of chemotherapy.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Ehrlich popularized the concepts of "magic bullet" drugs and of systematically improving drug therapies.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] His laboratory made decisive contributions to developing antiserum for diphtheria and standardizing therapeutic serums.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Early examples of organic reactions and applications were often found because of a combination of luck and preparation for unexpected observations.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] The latter half of the 19th century however witnessed systematic studies of organic compounds.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] The development of synthetic indigo is illustrative.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] The production of indigo from plant sources dropped from 19,000 tons in 1897 to 1,000 tons by 1914 thanks to the synthetic methods developed by Adolf von Baeyer.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] In 2002, 17,000 tons of synthetic indigo were produced from petrochemicals.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] In the early part of the 20th century, polymers and enzymes were shown to be large organic molecules, and petroleum was shown to be of biological origin.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] The multiple-step synthesis of complex organic compounds is called total synthesis.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Total synthesis of complex natural compounds increased in complexity to glucose and terpineol.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] For example, cholesterol-related compounds have opened ways to synthesize complex human hormones and their modified derivatives.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Since the start of the 20th century, complexity of total syntheses has been increased to include molecules of high complexity such as lysergic acid and vitamin B12.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] The discovery of petroleum and the development of the petrochemical industry spurred the development of organic chemistry.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] The majority of chemical compounds occurring in biological organisms are carbon compounds, so the association between organic chemistry and biochemistry is so close that biochemistry might be regarded as in essence a branch of organic chemistry.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Although the history of biochemistry might be taken to span some four centuries, fundamental understanding of the field only began to develop in the late 19th century and the actual term *biochemistry* was coined around the start of 20th century.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Since organic compounds often exist as mixtures, a variety of techniques have also been developed to assess purity; chromatography techniques are especially important for this application, and include HPLC and gas chromatography.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Traditional methods of separation include distillation, crystallization, evaporation, magnetic separation and solvent extraction.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Organic compounds were traditionally characterized by a variety of chemical tests, called "wet methods", but such tests have been largely displaced by spectroscopic or other computer-intensive methods of analysis.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Traditional spectroscopic methods such as infrared spectroscopy, optical rotation, and UV/VIS spectroscopy provide relatively nonspecific structural information but remain in use for specific applications.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Refractive index and density can also be important for substance identification.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] The physical properties of organic compounds typically of interest include both quantitative and qualitative features.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Quantitative information includes a melting point, boiling point, solubility, and index of refraction.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Qualitative properties include odor, consistency, and color.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Organic compounds typically melt and many boil.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] In contrast, while inorganic materials generally can be melted, many do not boil, and instead tend to degrade.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] In earlier times, the melting point (m.p.) and boiling point (b.p.) provided crucial information on the purity and identity of organic compounds.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] The melting and boiling points correlate with the polarity of the molecules and their molecular weight.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Some organic compounds, especially symmetrical ones, sublime.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] A well-known example of a sublimable organic compound is *para*-dichlorobenzene, the odiferous constituent of modern mothballs.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Organic compounds are usually not very stable at temperatures above 300 °C, although some exceptions exist.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Neutral organic compounds tend to be hydrophobic; that is, they are less soluble in water than in organic solvents.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Exceptions include organic compounds that contain ionizable groups as well as low molecular weight alcohols, amines, and carboxylic acids where hydrogen bonding occurs.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Otherwise, organic compounds tend to dissolve in organic solvents.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Solubility varies widely with the organic solute and with the organic solvent.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] For historical reasons, such properties are mainly the subjects of the areas of polymer science and materials science.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] The names of organic compounds are either systematic, following logically from a set of rules, or nonsystematic, following various traditions.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Systematic nomenclature is stipulated by specifications from IUPAC (International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry).
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Systematic nomenclature starts with the name for a parent structure within the molecule of interest.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] This parent name is then modified by prefixes, suffixes, and numbers to unambiguously convey the structure.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Given that millions of organic compounds are known, rigorous use of systematic names can be cumbersome.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Thus, IUPAC recommendations are more closely followed for simple compounds, but not complex molecules.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] To use the systematic naming, one must know the structures and names of the parent structures.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Parent structures include unsubstituted hydrocarbons, heterocycles, and monofunctionalized derivatives thereof.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Nonsystematic nomenclature is simpler and unambiguous, at least to organic chemists.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Nonsystematic names do not indicate the structure of the compound.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] They are common for complex molecules, which include most natural products.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Thus, the informally named lysergic acid diethylamide is systematically named (6a*R*,9*R*)-*N*,*N*-diethyl-7-methyl-4,6,6a,7,8,9-hexahydroindolo-[4,3-*fg*] quinoline-9-carboxamide.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] With the increased use of computing, other naming methods have evolved that are intended to be interpreted by machines.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Two popular formats are SMILES and InChI.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Organic molecules are described more commonly by drawings or structural formulas, combinations of drawings and chemical symbols.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] The line-angle formula is simple and unambiguous.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] In this system, the endpoints and intersections of each line represent one carbon, and hydrogen atoms can either be notated explicitly or assumed to be present as implied by tetravalent carbon.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] By 1880 an explosion in the number of chemical compounds being discovered occurred, assisted by new synthetic and analytical techniques.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Grignard described the situation as "chaos le plus complet" (complete chaos) due to the lack of convention, it was possible to have multiple names for the same compound.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] This led to the creation of the Geneva rules in 1892.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] The concept of functional groups is central in organic chemistry, both as a means to classify structures and for predicting properties.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] A functional group is a molecular module, and the reactivity of that functional group is assumed, within limits, to be the same in a variety of molecules.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Functional groups can have a decisive influence on the chemical and physical properties of organic compounds.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Molecules are classified based on their functional groups.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Alcohols, for example, all have the subunit C-O-H.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] All alcohols tend to be somewhat hydrophilic, usually form esters, and usually can be converted to the corresponding halides.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Most functional groups feature heteroatoms (atoms other than C and H).
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Organic compounds are classified according to functional groups, e.g., alcohols, carboxylic acids, amines, etc.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Functional groups make the molecule more acidic or basic due to their electronic influence on surrounding parts of the molecule.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] As the p*Ka* (aka basicity) of the molecular addition/functional group increases, there is a corresponding dipole, when measured, increases in strength.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] A dipole directed towards the functional group (higher p*Ka* therefore basic nature of group) points towards it and decreases in strength with increasing distance.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Dipole distance (measured in Angstroms) and steric hindrance towards the functional group have an intermolecular and intramolecular effect on the surrounding environment and pH level.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Different functional groups have different p*Ka* values and bond strengths (single, double, triple) leading to increased electrophilicity with lower p*Ka* and increased nucleophile strength with higher p*Ka*.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] More basic/nucleophilic functional groups desire to attack an electrophilic functional group with a lower p*Ka* on another molecule (intermolecular) or within the same molecule (intramolecular).
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Any group with a net acidic p*Ka* that gets within range, such as an acyl or carbonyl group is fair game.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Amines are very basic, and are great nucleophiles/attackers.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] The rest of the group is classified according to the functional groups present.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Such compounds can be "straight-chain", branched-chain or cyclic.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] The degree of branching affects characteristics, such as the octane number or cetane number in petroleum chemistry.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Both saturated (alicyclic) compounds and unsaturated compounds exist as cyclic derivatives.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] The most stable rings contain five or six carbon atoms, but large rings (macrocycles) and smaller rings are common.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] The smallest cycloalkane family is the three-membered cyclopropane ((CH2)3).
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Saturated cyclic compounds contain single bonds only, whereas aromatic rings have an alternating (or conjugated) double bond.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Cycloalkanes do not contain multiple bonds, whereas the cycloalkenes and the cycloalkynes do.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Aromatic hydrocarbons contain conjugated double bonds.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] This means that every carbon atom in the ring is sp2 hybridized, allowing for added stability.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] The most important example is benzene, the structure of which was formulated by Kekulé who first proposed the delocalization or resonance principle for explaining its structure.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] For "conventional" cyclic compounds, aromaticity is conferred by the presence of 4n + 2 delocalized pi electrons, where n is an integer.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Particular instability (antiaromaticity) is conferred by the presence of 4n conjugated pi electrons.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] The characteristics of the cyclic hydrocarbons are again altered if heteroatoms are present, which can exist as either substituents attached externally to the ring (exocyclic) or as a member of the ring itself (endocyclic).
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] In the case of the latter, the ring is termed a heterocycle.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Pyridine and furan are examples of aromatic heterocycles while piperidine and tetrahydrofuran are the corresponding alicyclic heterocycles.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] The heteroatom of heterocyclic molecules is generally oxygen, sulfur, or nitrogen, with the latter being particularly common in biochemical systems.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Heterocycles are commonly found in a wide range of products including aniline dyes and medicines.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Additionally, they are prevalent in a wide range of biochemical compounds such as alkaloids, vitamins, steroids, and nucleic acids (e.g.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Rings can fuse with other rings on an edge to give polycyclic compounds.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] The purine nucleoside bases are notable polycyclic aromatic heterocycles.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Rings can also fuse on a "corner" such that one atom (almost always carbon) has two bonds going to one ring and two to another.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Such compounds are termed *spiro* and are important in several natural products.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] One important property of carbon is that it readily forms chains, or networks, that are linked by carbon-carbon (carbon-to-carbon) bonds.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] The linking process is called polymerization, while the chains, or networks, are called polymers.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] The source compound is called a monomer.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Two main groups of polymers exist: synthetic polymers and biopolymers.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Synthetic polymers are artificially manufactured, and are commonly referred to as industrial polymers.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Biopolymers occur within a respectfully natural environment, or without human intervention.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Biomolecular chemistry is a major category within organic chemistry which is frequently studied by biochemists.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Many complex multi-functional group molecules are important in living organisms.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Some are long-chain biopolymers, and these include peptides, DNA, RNA and the polysaccharides such as starches in animals and celluloses in plants.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] The other main classes are amino acids (monomer building blocks of peptides and proteins), carbohydrates (which includes the polysaccharides), the nucleic acids (which include DNA and RNA as polymers), and the lipids.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Besides, animal biochemistry contains many small molecule intermediates which assist in energy production through the Krebs cycle, and produces isoprene, the most common hydrocarbon in animals.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Biologists usually classify the above-mentioned biomolecules into four main groups, i.e., proteins, lipids, carbohydrates, and nucleic acids.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Petroleum and its derivatives are considered organic molecules, which is consistent with the fact that this oil comes from the fossilization of living beings, i.e., biomolecules.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] See also: peptide synthesis, oligonucleotide synthesis and carbohydrate synthesis.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] In pharmacology, an important group of organic compounds is small molecules, also referred to as "small organic compounds".
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] In this context, a small molecule is a small organic compound that is biologically active but is not a polymer.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] In practice, small molecules have a molar mass less than approximately 1000 g/mol.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Fullerenes and carbon nanotubes, carbon compounds with spheroidal and tubular structures, have stimulated much research into the related field of materials science.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] The first fullerene was discovered in 1985 by Sir Harold W.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Kroto of the United Kingdom and by Richard E.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] In 1996 the trio was awarded the Nobel Prize for their pioneering efforts.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] The C60 molecule was named buckminsterfullerene (or, more simply, the buckyball) after the American architect R.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Buckminster Fuller, whose geodesic dome is constructed on the same structural principles.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Organic compounds containing bonds of carbon to nitrogen, oxygen and the halogens are not normally grouped separately.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Others are sometimes put into major groups within organic chemistry and discussed under titles such as organosulfur chemistry, organometallic chemistry, organophosphorus chemistry and organosilicon chemistry.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Organic reactions are chemical reactions involving organic compounds.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Many of these reactions are associated with functional groups.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] The general theory of these reactions involves careful analysis of such properties as the electron affinity of key atoms, bond strengths and steric hindrance.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] These factors can determine the relative stability of short-lived reactive intermediates, which usually directly determine the path of the reaction.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] The basic reaction types are: addition reactions, elimination reactions, substitution reactions, pericyclic reactions, rearrangement reactions and redox reactions.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] where X is some functional group and Nu is a nucleophile.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] The number of possible organic reactions is infinite.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] However, certain general patterns are observed that can be used to describe many common or useful reactions.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Each reaction has a stepwise reaction mechanism that explains how it happens in sequence—although the detailed description of steps is not always clear from a list of reactants alone.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] The stepwise course of any given reaction mechanism can be represented using arrow pushing techniques in which curved arrows are used to track the movement of electrons as starting materials transition through intermediates to final products.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] The mechanism for certain organic reactions remain subjects of ongoing debate and have not been fully elucidated.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Synthetic organic chemistry is an applied science as it borders engineering, the "design, analysis, and/or construction of works for practical purposes".
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Organic synthesis of a novel compound is a problem-solving task, where a synthesis is designed for a target molecule by selecting optimal reactions from optimal starting materials.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Complex compounds can have tens of reaction steps that sequentially build the desired molecule.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] The synthesis proceeds by utilizing the reactivity of the functional groups in the molecule.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] For example, a carbonyl compound can be used as a nucleophile by converting it into an enolate, or as an electrophile; the combination of the two is called the aldol reaction.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Designing practically useful syntheses always requires conducting the actual synthesis in the laboratory.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] The scientific practice of creating novel synthetic routes for complex molecules is called total synthesis.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Strategies to design a synthesis include retrosynthesis, popularized by E.J.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Corey, which starts with the target molecule and splices it to pieces according to known reactions.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] The pieces, or the proposed precursors, receive the same treatment, until available and ideally inexpensive starting materials are reached.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] Then, the retrosynthesis is written in the opposite direction to give the synthesis.
[src:organic-chemistry/organic-chemistry] A "synthetic tree" can be constructed because each compound and also each precursor has multiple syntheses.
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] In chemistry, a **reaction mechanism** is the step by step sequence of elementary reactions by which overall chemical reaction occurs.
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] A chemical mechanism is a theoretical conjecture that tries to describe in detail what takes place at each stage of an overall chemical reaction.
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] The detailed steps of a reaction are not observable in most cases.
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] The conjectured mechanism is chosen because it is thermodynamically feasible and has experimental support in isolated intermediates (see next section) or other quantitative and qualitative characteristics of the reaction.
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] It also describes each reactive intermediate, activated complex, and transition state, which bonds are broken (and in what order), and which bonds are formed (and in what order).
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] A complete mechanism must also explain the reason for the reactants and catalyst used, the stereochemistry observed in reactants and products, all products formed and the amount of each.
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] The electron or arrow pushing method is often used in illustrating a reaction mechanism; for example, see the illustrations of the mechanisms for Michael addition and benzoin condensation in the following examples section.
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] Mechanisms also are of interest in inorganic chemistry.
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] An often quoted mechanistic experiment involved the reaction of the labile hexaaquo chromous reductant with the exchange inert pentammine cobalt(III) chloride.
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] Reaction intermediates are chemical species, often unstable and short-lived.
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] They can, however, sometimes be isolated.
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] They are neither reactants nor products of the overall chemical reaction, but temporary products and/or reactants in the mechanism's reaction steps.
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] Reaction intermediates are often confused with the transition state.
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] The transition states are, in contrast, fleeting, high-energy species that cannot be isolated.
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] Information about the mechanism of a reaction is often provided by analyzing chemical kinetics to determine the reaction order in each reactant.
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] The rate law for this reaction is: $r=k[NO_{2}]^{2}$ This form shows that the rate-determining step does not involve CO.
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] Instead, the slow step involves two molecules of NO2.
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] Each step is called an elementary step, and each has its own rate law and molecularity.
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] The sum of the elementary steps gives the net reaction.
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] When determining the overall rate law for a reaction, the slowest step is the step that determines the reaction rate.
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] Because the first step (in the above reaction) is the slowest step, it is the rate-determining step.
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] Because it involves the collision of two NO2 molecules, it is a bimolecular reaction with a rate r which obeys the rate law $r=k[NO_{2}(t)]^{2}$ .
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] Other reactions may have mechanisms of several consecutive steps.
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] In organic chemistry, the reaction mechanism for the benzoin condensation, put forward in 1903 by A.
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] Lapworth, was one of the first proposed reaction mechanisms.
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] A chain reaction is an example of a complex mechanism, in which the propagation steps form a closed cycle.
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] In a chain reaction, the intermediate produced in one step generates an intermediate in another step.
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] Intermediates are called chain carriers.
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] Sometimes, the chain carriers are radicals, they can be ions as well.
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] Propagation: a chain carrier makes another carrier.
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] Branching: one carrier makes more than one carrier.
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] Retardation: a chain carrier may react with a product reducing the rate of formation of the product.
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] It makes another chain carrier, but the product concentration is reduced.
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] Chain termination: radicals combine and the chain carriers are lost.
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] Inhibition: chain carriers are removed by processes other than termination, such as by forming radicals.
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] Even though all these steps can appear in one chain reaction, the minimum necessary ones are Initiation, propagation, and termination.
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] An example of a simple chain reaction is the thermal decomposition of acetaldehyde (CH3CHO) to methane (CH4) and carbon monoxide (CO).
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] The experimental reaction order is 3/2, which can be explained by a *Rice-Herzfeld mechanism*.
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] For the overall reaction, the rates of change of the concentration of the intermediates •CH3 and CH3CO• are zero, according to the steady-state approximation, which is used to account for the rate laws of chain reactions.
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] The sum of these two equations is k1[CH3CHO] – 2 k4[•CH3]2 = 0.
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] This may be solved to find the steady-state concentration of •CH3 radicals as [•CH3] = (k1 / 2k4)1/2 [CH3CHO]1/2.
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] Thus the mechanism explains the observed rate expression, for the principal products CH4 and CO.
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] The exact rate law may be even more complicated, there are also minor products such as acetone (CH3COCH3) and propanal (CH3CH2CHO).
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] A correct reaction mechanism is an important part of accurate predictive modeling.
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] For many combustion and plasma systems, detailed mechanisms are not available or require development.
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] Even when information is available, identifying and assembling the relevant data from a variety of sources, reconciling discrepant values and extrapolating to different conditions can be a difficult process without expert help.
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] Rate constants or thermochemical data are often not available in the literature, so computational chemistry techniques or group additivity methods must be used to obtain the required parameters.
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] Computational chemistry methods can also be used to calculate potential energy surfaces for reactions and determine probable mechanisms.
[src:organic-chemistry/reaction-mechanism] In general, reaction steps involving more than three molecular entities do not occur, because is statistically improbable in terms of Maxwell distribution to find such a transition state.
[src:organic-chemistry/stereochemistry] Stereochemistry also studies the reactivity of the molecules in question (dynamic stereochemistry).
[src:organic-chemistry/stereochemistry] Cahn–Ingold–Prelog priority rules are part of a system for describing a molecule's stereochemistry.
[src:organic-chemistry/stereochemistry] They rank the atoms around a stereochemical region of a molecule in a standard way, allowing unambiguous descriptions of their relative positions in the molecule.
[src:organic-chemistry/stereochemistry] Rather than using a high-quality 3D rendering a molecule, there are several simplified standard ways of representing the 3D positioning of atoms around a stereocenter.
[src:organic-chemistry/stereochemistry] One common convention uses a bond drawn as a solid wedge to indicate that a bond that is projecting towards the viewer, a dashed or hashed bond to indicate that a bond is receding away from the viewer, and plain lines to represent bonds that are in the plane of the molecule itself.
[src:organic-chemistry/stereochemistry] A Fischer projection represents the four directions around a tetrahedral atom by drawing the bonds horizontally or vertically, with vertical meaning the bond recedes away from the viewer and horizontal meaning the bond projects towards the viewer.
[src:organic-chemistry/stereochemistry] Stereochemistry has important applications in the field of medicine, particularly pharmaceuticals.
[src:organic-chemistry/stereochemistry] An often cited example of the importance of stereochemistry relates to the thalidomide disaster.
[src:organic-chemistry/stereochemistry] Thalidomide is a pharmaceutical drug, first prepared in 1957 in Germany, prescribed for treating morning sickness in pregnant women.
[src:organic-chemistry/stereochemistry] The drug was discovered to be teratogenic, causing serious genetic damage to early embryonic growth and development, leading to limb deformation in babies.
[src:organic-chemistry/stereochemistry] Several proposed mechanisms of teratogenicity involve different biological functions for the (R)- and (S)-thalidomide enantiomers.
[src:organic-chemistry/stereochemistry] In the human body, however, thalidomide undergoes racemization: even if only one of the two enantiomers is administered as a drug, the other enantiomer is produced as a result of metabolism.
[src:organic-chemistry/stereochemistry] Accordingly, it is incorrect to state that one stereoisomer is safe while the other is teratogenic.
[src:organic-chemistry/stereochemistry] Thalidomide is currently used for the treatment of other diseases, notably cancer and leprosy.
[src:organic-chemistry/stereochemistry] Strict regulations and controls have been implemented to avoid its use by pregnant women and prevent developmental deformities.
[src:organic-chemistry/stereochemistry] This disaster was a driving force behind requiring strict testing of drugs before making them available to the public.
[src:organic-chemistry/stereochemistry] In yet another example, the drug ibuprofen can exist as (R)- and (S)-isomers.
[src:organic-chemistry/stereochemistry] Only the (S)-ibuprofen is active in reducing inflammation and pain.
[src:organic-chemistry/stereochemistry] Isomers are of two types: diastereomers (also called diastereoisomers) and enantiomers.
[src:organic-chemistry/stereochemistry] Enantiomers are non-superimposable mirror images.
[src:organic-chemistry/stereochemistry] Diastereomers are all other types of isomers.
[src:organic-chemistry/stereochemistry] Epimers are a subcategory of diastereomers that differ in absolute configuration configurations at only one corresponding stereocenter.
[src:organic-chemistry/stereochemistry] They are commonly found in sugar chemistry, where two sugars can differ by the configuration of a single carbon atom.
[src:organic-chemistry/stereochemistry] D-glucose and D-galactose are epimers, differing only at the C-4 position in their structure.
[src:organic-chemistry/stereochemistry] Cis-Trans isomers are often associated alkene double bonds.
[src:organic-chemistry/stereochemistry] The more general *E*/*Z* nomenclature refers to the concept of *cis*/*trans* isomerism, and is especially useful for more complex compounds.
[src:organic-chemistry/stereochemistry] Atropisomerism are another kind of diasteromer.
[src:organic-chemistry/stereochemistry] They exist because of the inability to rotate about a bond, such as due to steric hindrance between functional groups on two sp2-hybridized carbon atoms.
[src:organic-chemistry/stereochemistry] Usually atropisomers are chiral, and as such they are a form of axial chirality.
[src:organic-chemistry/stereochemistry] In 1815, Jean-Baptiste Biot's observation of optical activity marked the beginning of organic stereochemistry history.
[src:organic-chemistry/stereochemistry] He observed that organic molecules were able to rotate the plane of polarized light in a solution or in the gaseous phase.
[src:organic-chemistry/stereochemistry] Despite Biot's discoveries, Louis Pasteur is commonly described as the first stereochemist, having observed in 1842 that salts of tartaric acid collected from wine production vessels could rotate the plane of polarized light, but that salts from other sources did not.
[src:organic-chemistry/stereochemistry] This was the only physical property that differed between the two types of tartrate salts, which is due to optical isomerism.
[src:organic-chemistry/stereochemistry] In 1874, Jacobus Henricus van 't Hoff and Joseph Le Bel explained optical activity in terms of the tetrahedral arrangement of the atoms bound to carbon.
[src:organic-chemistry/stereochemistry] Kekulé explored tetrahedral models earlier, in 1862, but never published his work; Emanuele Paternò probably knew of these but was the first to draw and discuss three dimensional structures, such as of 1,2-dibromoethane in the *Giornale di Scienze Naturali ed Economiche* in 1869.
[src:organic-chemistry/stereochemistry] The term "chiral" was introduced by Lord Kelvin in 1904.
[src:organic-chemistry/stereochemistry] Arthur Robertson Cushny, a Scottish Pharmacologist, first provided a clear example in 1908 of a bioactivity difference between enantiomers of a chiral molecule viz.
[src:organic-chemistry/stereochemistry] (−)-Adrenaline is two times more potent than the (±)- form as a vasoconstrictor and in 1926 laid the foundation for chiral pharmacology/stereo-pharmacology (biological relations of optically isomeric substances).
[src:organic-chemistry/stereochemistry] Later in 1966, the Cahn–Ingold–Prelog nomenclature or Sequence rule was devised to assign absolute configuration to stereogenic/chiral center (R- and S- notation) and extended to be applied across olefinic bonds (E- and Z- notation).
